---
import PageLayout from "@/layouts/Base";
import { Icon } from "astro-icon";

const meta = {
	title: "Coffee Galley",
	description:
		"A Shiny app for Shopify stores to sell custom-label coffee products, manage catalogue items, and handle fulfilment workflows.",
};
---

<PageLayout meta={meta}>
	<div class="max-w-2xl">
		<div class="mb-8 flex items-center gap-4">
			<img src="/ship_logo.png" alt="Coffee Galley ship icon" class="h-20 w-20 rounded-2xl" />
			<div>
				<h1 class="title mb-1 text-3xl">Coffee Galley</h1>
				<p class="text-gray-500">2020-2022</p>
			</div>
		</div>

		<section class="mb-8">
			<p class="mb-4">
				Coffee Galley was a Shopify app I made as my first real app project. The idea was to give
				Shopify merchants an easy way to add custom-label coffee products to their stores without
				dealing with roasting, packaging, labels, or fulfilment.
			</p>
			<p class="mb-4">
				All they had to do was upload their logo. The app would create 3D renders of the packages,
				create the Shopify products, and handle all communication with the roaster so fulfilment and
				delivery happened without merchant intervention. Everything was fully automated.
			</p>
			<p class="mb-4">It basically provided dropshipping for coffee brands.</p>
			<p>
				The front end was made with the Shiny framework, the backend was made with Plumber, and all
				data management was handled with either SQL or .rds files. Which means everything was made
				in pure R code. This gave me the excuse to present at a few conferences about the unexpected
				use cases of R outside statistics. You can do anything with R. Should you, though? Probably
				not. But you can.
			</p>
		</section>

		<div class="mb-12 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
			<a
				href="#"
				class="inline-flex cursor-default items-center gap-2 rounded-md bg-accent px-4 py-2 text-bgColor opacity-60"
			>
				<Icon name="fa-brands:shopify" class="h-5 w-5" />
				 Shopify App Store
			</a>
		</div>
	</div>
</PageLayout>
